# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball5-european-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] It took place in Baku, Azerbaijan, from 12 to 28 June 2015, and featured almost 6,000 athletes from 50 countries competing in 30 sports, including 15 summer Olympic and 2 non-Olympic sports.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Baku was awarded the right to host the first European Games at the 41st EOC General Assembly in Rome, on 8 December 2012.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The European Games would take place every four years thereafter, with the next competition held in 2019.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The decision was made as a result of secret balloting, where of 48 votes, 38 were in favour of the sole bidder for the event.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Eight votes were against, and two more abstained from voting.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The representatives of Armenia refused to take part in the voting.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The Organising Committee responsible for the inaugural European Games in Baku was established by decree of the president of the Republic of Azerbaijan.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The committee is chaired by the First Lady of Azerbaijan Mehriban Aliyeva, member of the Executive Committee of the National Olympic Committee of the Republic of Azerbaijan and UNESCO Goodwill Ambassador.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Baku 2015 European Games Operations Committee (BEGOC) was established under the direction of the chairperson of the Organising Committee.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The Chief Executive Officer of BEGOC is Azad Rahimov, Minister of Youth and Sport while the Chief Operating Officer is Simon Clegg.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] There were four clusters and 18 competition venues for the inaugural European Games, including 12 that were designed to become permanent venues.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Five of the venues were new-builds: the National Gymnastics Arena, BMX Velopark, Baku Aquatics Centre, Baku Shooting Centre and National Stadium.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] There were six temporary venues: Water Polo Arena, Beach Arena, Basketball Arena, Mountain Bike Velopark, Triathlon, Cycling road race and time trial.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The Athletes Village, located in the Nizami raion of Baku, comprises 13 buildings, 16 different types of apartments with three to four bedrooms per apartment.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The local organising committee launched an online sales page on its website to allow fans purchasing tickets for the inaugural event.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Adult tickets for sport sessions range between AZN 2 – AZN 5, according to competition round (for example preliminary or final), seat category, and venue.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Organisers aimed to recruit 12,500 volunteers to play roles during the Games, including assisting athletes and dignitaries, working at sport competitions, or providing assistance to spectators or the media.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Baku 2015 European Games volunteers were called Flamekeepers.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] 6,000 Ceremonies Performers voluntarily took part in the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The closing ceremony was held on 28 June in the National Stadium.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] James Hadley was the artistic director and Christian Steinhäuser the music director of the closing ceremony.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] 50 national olympic committees participated in this European Games edition, including the Olympic Committee of Kosovo in its first time at a wide multi-sport event.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Since the Faroe Islands and Gibraltar are not members of the European Olympic Committee, the Faroese participants occurred for the Ligue Européenne de Natation and the Gibraltar participants for the Athletic Association of Small States of Europe.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] A total of 20 sports were represented: 16 Olympic sports, two Olympic sports contested only in non-Olympic formats (basketball and football) and two non-Olympic sports (karate and sambo).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Two para-sport events were contested judo.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Twelve of the sports (archery, athletics, boxing, cycling, judo, shooting, swimming, table tennis, taekwondo, triathlon, volleyball, wrestling) would offer qualification opportunities for the Rio 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The aquatic sports are only open to junior-level competitors, and the athletics competition forms the third division of the European Team Championships.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The competition schedule consists of 253 events.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The International Sports Broadcasting (ISB) and Olympic Broadcasting Services are the host broadcasters of the European Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] During the Games, ISB was anticipated to produce 800 hours of broadcast coverage.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Amnesty International have been a vocal critic of the Baku 2015 European Games, stating in March 2015, "Azerbaijan may be a safe country for athletes taking part in the 100 metres, but defending rights and free speech is a dangerous game here.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Those who champion them receive harassment and prison sentences instead of medals.".
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] In August 2014, the human rights organisation highlighted the 24 prisoners of conscience being held in Azerbaijan prisons as an example of abuses.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Western countries also criticized Aliyev's intention to close the OSCE offices in Baku.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] In June 2015, *The Guardian* reported that its own reporters, along with those of other media outlets, had been barred from entering Baku to cover the games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Human Rights Watch, in the same article, stated it had observed "the worst crackdown the country has seen in the post-Soviet era".
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Most European heads of state and government refused to participate at the opening ceremony, sending mid- or low-level representatives instead.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Among those who did participate were Vladimir Putin of Russia, Recep Tayyip Erdoğan of Turkey, Aleksander Lukashenko of Belarus, Boyko Borisov of Bulgaria and Victor Ponta of Romania.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Ponta and Borisov faced criticism at home for their participation.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] During the games there was a road accident where a coach driver drove into a group of young Austrian athletes by mixing up the accelerator and brake pedals, with the incident recorded by a surveillance camera.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] 15-year-old Austrian synchronized swimmer Vanessa Sahinovic and her teammates Lisa Breit and Luna Pajer were injured.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Sahinovic was placed in an induced coma and flown to Vienna for emergency surgery.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Sahinovic was left paraplegic in the accident.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Because of the accident, Austria had to withdraw from the team competition.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] In the synchronized swimming duet competition, sisters Anna-Maria and Eirini-Maria Alexandri won the silver medal, which they dedicated to the injured teammates.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The police officer who released the video of the surveillance camera was relieved of his duties.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Sahinovic is recovering, and is supported by an initiative of Austrian swimmers and a fundraising campaign.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The official logo for the 2015 European Games was unveiled on 16 June 2014.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Designed by Adam Yunusov, it was inspired by country's contemporary culture.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The logo includes flame, water, the mythical Simurgh bird, an Azerbaijani carpet and a pomegranate as one of the symbols of Azerbaijani profusion.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The pomegranate, called *Nar* (pomegranate in Azerbaijani), is one of two mascots for the Games, along with a gazelle named *Jeyran* (gazelle in Azerbaijani).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The couple are intended to represent the spirit of Azerbaijan and help excite the youth for the event.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The brand incorporates traditional Azerbaijani imagery with images and colours designed to evoke a European sporting feel.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The pomegranate tree, whose fruit juice is one of Azerbaijan's main exports, features heavily.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The brand was created with legacy potential in mind, possibly inspired by the way the Commonwealth Games’ branding retains a similar feel each year.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] As Azerbaijan as a state sponsored Spanish football club Atlético Madrid at that time, this European Games was advertised on the club's kits during the later half of their 2014–15 season.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] On 21 May 2014, Procter & Gamble became the first official partner of the inaugural European Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] Swiss watchmaker Tissot has been named the official timekeeper and will provide all timing and scoring services.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] On 13 November 2014, Motorola Solutions also teamed up with Baku 2015 as the Official Radio Communications Supporter.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] On Sunday 26 April the president of the Republic of Azerbaijan, Ilham Aliyev, captured the official flame of the Baku 2015 European Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2015-european-games] The flame had visited 60 locations until the final torchbearer entered the National Stadium for the Opening Ceremony on 12 June.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] The **2018 European Championships** were the first edition of the European Championships.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] It was a multi-sport event which took place in Berlin, Germany, and Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom (with Edinburgh hosting the diving events and Gleneagles the golf) from 2 to 12 August 2018.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] Around 1,500 athletes competed at the European Athletics Championships in Berlin, whilst at the same time more than 3,000 took part in the other championships in Glasgow.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] Each European Championship was organised by the respective federation and host city.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] On 1 August, at the "Great Big Opening Party" in Glasgow, a new European Championship Trophy was unveiled, which was awarded to the nation achieving the most gold medals across all seven sports during the Championships.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] It was presented by Katherine Grainger, Emma Fredh and Angelina Melnikova on behalf of the seven European federations involved in the event.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] On 12 August, the trophy was presented to the leading nation on the overall table, Russia, in a ceremony in Glasgow.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] The original schedule was released in February 2017.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] The schedule was updated in June 2017 based on the Glasgow ticket schedule and again in March 2018 when the Berlin timetable was released.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] Each sport maintained its own medal table, but an overall medal table is also maintained, the leader of which won the European Championship trophy.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] Russia won the inaugural trophy and topped the medal table by gold medals won with 31, whilst co-hosts Great Britain topped the total medals table with 74 medals, 26 of which were gold.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] A chasing pack consisting of Italy, the Netherlands, co-hosts Germany and France each won over 10 gold medals and 40 medals in total.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] In addition, while both the Men's and Women's Gymnastics events included junior competitions in line with previous editions, medals in those competitions are not included within the total.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] All of Europe's major free-to-air broadcasters televised the European Championships in 2018, such as BBC in the United Kingdom, ARD/ZDF in Germany, France Télévisions in France, RAI in Italy and TVE in Spain.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] Other EBU members who signed up include VRT (Belgium), HRT (Croatia), DR (Denmark), YLE (Finland), RTÉ (Ireland), NOS (Netherlands), NRK (Norway), TVP (Poland), RTP (Portugal), SRG SSR (Switzerland) and SVT (Sweden).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] The level of coverage was also enhanced by a deal with Eurosport.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] In total, over 40 EBU members signed agreements as of April 2018.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] There were discussions with broadcasters in the remaining territories in Europe, plus other global territories like China, Japan and USA.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] Glasgow 2018 had five official partners (People Make Glasgow, Scottish Government, Strathmore Water, Spar & Eurovision) and Berlin 2018 had six official partners (Spar, Le Gruyère, Nike, Toyo Tires, Generali & Eurovision) with another tier of official supporters across the two host cities.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2018-european-championships] Overall over 56 companies signed up to support the inaugural event.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The games featured 200 events in 15 sports (23 disciplines).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Around 4,000 athletes from 50 countries participated.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Ten of the sports offered qualification opportunities for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The opening ceremony at the Dinamo Stadium was held on 21 June, and the closing ceremony at the same venue was held on 30 June.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] A number of countries and cities expressed their interest to host the second European Games in 2019 but only the Netherlands submitted an official bid.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] At the meeting of an Extraordinary General Assembly on 16 May 2015, the Netherlands was unanimously approved as host of the second edition of the Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The competition intended to be nationwide and based in seven cities, including Amsterdam, The Hague, Eindhoven, Rotterdam, Utrecht.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On 10 June 2015, the Netherlands announced their refusal to hold the second European Games after insufficient funding for the Games, projected to cost €57.5m.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The European Olympic Committee president, Patrick Hickey said the news was "disappointing".
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Following this, a number of countries expressed interest in hosting the games: Belarus (Minsk), United Kingdom (Glasgow), Poland (Poznań), Russia (Kazan and Sochi), Turkey (Istanbul).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In November 2015, Russia was announced as a future host country for the II European Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] At the same time, the WADA began its investigation of the doping scandal in Russia which led to the IOC's refusal to support the holding of major sports events in Russia, including the second European Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] During the meeting of the EOC General Assembly, held in Minsk on 21 October 2016, Minsk was selected as a host city for the second European Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On 12 May 2017, the President of Belarus Alexander Lukashenko signed a decree on the Foundation of the Directorate of the II European Games 2019.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The founders of the foundation are the National Olympic Committee, the Minsk City Executive Committee and the Ministry of Sports and Tourism.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Georgy Katulin, General Secretary of the National Olympic Committee of the Republic of Belarus, was appointed the CEO of the foundation in August 2017.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In November 2017, the management launched the official website of the games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In April 2019, Lukashenko announced that the Games were on budget and on time and that "everything should meet the highest standards".
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Sergei Rumas, Belarus's prime minister and the head of the Organising Committee also said that all the facilities would be finished by 15 May and that "95 per cent of the equipment has already been installed".
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On 20 May 2019, Lukashenko signed Decree No.191, entitled "On security measures during the 2nd European Games in Belarus".
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] It gave the Ministry of Defence the power to restrict access to certain areas and placed a ban on drones, unmanned aerial vehicles and model aeroplanes at competition venues.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Drones and planes violating the decree will be seized until 2 July, when the Games end.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The start of the volunteer selection began in September 2017 during the "Dobrofest" and registration ended on 1 April 2019.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In April 2019, the head of the volunteer network for the Games, Nadezhda Anisovets, said that the appeal resulted in 24,000 applications, much larger than the 8,000 needed for the Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Most of them are students of Belarusian universities.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Applications were also received from 52 other countries including Russia, Australia, the USA, Mexico, and Egypt.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The basic requirements for the candidate are communication skills and high English-language proficiency.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The selected volunteers will be involved in over 34 functional areas.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Each volunteer will be given a special uniform, badges and souvenirs.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On June 30, 2019, Tony Moore performed his composition “We Are The Light” at the closing ceremony of the European Games 2019 in Belarus.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The song was written to honour the 8000 volunteers who helped host the Euro Games in Minsk 2019.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On 27 December 2017, it was announced about the finalising of the development of a comprehensive transport service plan for the competition, based on the needs of all stakeholders and the experience of the previous Olympic and European Games host cities: Beijing, London, Baku.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The main goal of the developed plan is to optimise the routes in such a way that any participant can get to any stadium in no more than half an hour.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Rail services between Masyukovshchina (Minsk-Arena), Belarus (regatta course Zaslawye) and Loshitsa (Čyžoŭka-Arena) will operate with higher frequency during the event.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In addition, the existing bus network will be expanded by 10 to 12 new routes to the competition sites, which will run up to 300 buses and trolleybuses.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In August 2018, new digital information boards were unveiled in order to improve the public transport network for foreign visitors.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Valery Shkuratov, the director of Metropolitan Transport and Communications (the firm which manage the transit systems in the city), said that more than 270 displays had already been installed.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In October 2018, it was announced that the Minsk metro would have full 4G coverage by the time the Games began.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The next month, fourteen taxi companies in Minsk as well as several governmental and administrational departments signed a memorandum of understanding to guarantee fair prices during the Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In March 2019, it was announced that the taxis adhering to the scheme would carry a logo to enable customers to identify them.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The Organising committee plans to involve already existed sports facilities after their renovation.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The Opening and closing ceremonies, as well as competitions in track and field, will be held at the Dinamo Stadium (Minsk, Kirov, 8).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Athletes, team officials and other team personnel will stay on the grounds of Minsk University, which has the capacity to host up to 7,500 people.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The students have been evicted for the duration of the Games and given alternative accommodation.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Part of the village facilities has already been put into operation, part of it will be completed by April 2019.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Each apartment has two bedrooms and can hold up to 4 people.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The village also has a canteen, gym, merchandise store and cultural centre.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The torch relay "Flame of Peace" was planned for before the games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In addition to traditional running with a torch, there were also creative performances organised along the route.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The torch relay will last for 50 days and will cover 7,700 km.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The relay will include 450 torchbearers, 100 volunteers and 10 flame keepers.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The torch relay will begin on 3 May in Rome.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The torch itself was designed by Yulia Braychuk, weighs 1.7 kg and is 81 cm tall.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] It is made from stainless steel and can be attached to a bike or wheelchair.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] All fifty European Olympic Committees member countries competed at the Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Numbers in brackets denote the number of athletes being sent to the Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The Opening ceremony was held at National Olympic Stadium Dinamo and ran from 22:10 to 00:45 FET.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] It was produced by Russian company Art City 5, and was directed by Alexander Vavilov (Belarus) and Alexei Sechenov (Russia).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Augmented reality imagery was used during the ceremony.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The main musical performers were Anna Netrebko, Ilya Silchukov with Elena Salo and Dimash Kudaibergen.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] During the parade of nations, Greece entered the stadium first.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The host nation Belarus marched last, while other countries entered in English alphabetical order.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Each delegation is escorted by girls in dresses representing the Kupala wheel, a symbol of the sun for Eastern Slavs decorated with traditional Belarusian ornaments.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Georgian President Salome Zourabichvili, who was due to attend the ceremony, left early due to the civil unrest in the Georgian capital of Tbilisi.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] A total of 15 sports were presented: archery, athletics, badminton, 3x3 basketball, beach football, boxing, canoe sprint, cycling, gymnastics, judo, karate, sambo, shooting, table tennis and wrestling.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] A number of disciplines were dropped after the 2015 European Games: all aquatics (diving, swimming, synchronised swimming and water polo), BMX racing, mountain biking, fencing, taekwondo, triathlon and all volleyball (beach volleyball and indoor volleyball).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The competition schedule consists of 200 events.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The Closing ceremony was held at National Olympic Stadium Dinamo and ran from 22:00 to 23:50 FET.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In attendance were IOC President Thomas Bach, Russian President Vladimir Putin, Tajik President Emomali Rahmon, and Armenian President Armen Sarkissian.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The prototype for creating the 2nd European Games' logo in Minsk was the Kupala fire and "paparats-kvetka", which plays an important role in .
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The logo of the Games was "paparać-kvietka" (Belarusian: папараць-кветка, romanized: *paparats-kvyetka*)—a plant that plays an important role in the culture of the Slavic culture.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] According to legend, the mythical flower blossoms once a year at midnight on Kupala Night.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Anyone who sees this flowering will become the owner of unusual abilities and talents.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The slogan of the event is "Bright Year, Bright You", which also makes reference to the national domain of the Republic of Belarus and the official international shortening—BY.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In autumn of 2017, an open republican contest for the development of the mascot of the European Games was announced.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Anyone could take part in the competition.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Over 2,000 variants were collected from professionals and amateurs.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The public presentation of the winning version took place in Minsk on 29 November 2018.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The mascot chosen was a baby fox named "Lesik" who wears a shirt and shorts with the colours of the games' logo and wears shoes and a baseball hat with the games' slogan.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Lesik's story is based after The Little Prince, when after the Little Prince leaves Earth, Lesik the Fox misses his new friend and wants to make more.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] He learns of a legendary flower called the Paparats Kvetka which can help his dream come true, but he needs to travel 1 million steps to Belarus to find it.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] He represents friendship, development, harmony, discipline, determination, cheerfulness, invincibility and vigour, according to the mascot's creators.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The slogan of the event is "Bright Year, Bright You!", which also successfully points to the national domain of the Republic of Belarus and the official international abbreviation BY.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] Sponsorship was approved as one of the sources to reduce the number of budgetary funds for the games according to the decree of the President of the Republic of Belarus of 12 May 2017 «On the Directorate of the second European Games 2019».
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On 15 December 2017, the official sponsor of the games became the operator of electronic interactive games «Sport Pari».
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On 22 December 2017, it was announced that the telecommunication operator velcom is the official telecommunication partner of the 2nd European Games of 2019.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In March 2019, the Games' Organising Committee signed a memorandum of understanding with UNAIDS to strengthen co-operation in promoting safe lifestyles, preventing the spread of HIV/AIDS and eliminating discrimination around the infection.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The deadline for submitting the selfie photos was October 2018.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The criteria for evaluating photos include compliance with the theme and conditions of the contest, as well as artistic taste and originality.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The final results were to be announced in late December 2018; however, the competition was extended to the 31 December.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] It was then later announced that the deadline would be extended again to the 25 February 2019.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The winners were awarded diplomas from Belteleradiocompany, as well as sets of tickets for the events of the European Games in Minsk and the official gear of the National Team of the Republic of Belarus.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] It happened on 21 June, nearly 30 minutes prior to Opening Ceremony of the Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] On 1 February 2019, Belposhta, the Belarusian postal service, released the official stamps for the Games.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The four designs depict a cyclist, a runner, a rower and a dancer and were designed by Marina Vitkovskaya, with 120,000 sets being printed.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] There was an official cancellation ceremony in Minsk City Hall on the day of release.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In February 2019, International Sports Broadcasting, a Spanish firm, was chosen as the host broadcaster for the Games, beating Match TV and Medialuso-Mediapro.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] The company had previously broadcast the 1st European Games in Baku.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] In March 2019, ISB was allowed to sell global broadcasting rights for the Games, with around 117 countries that have already been granted viewing rights.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2019-european-games] ISB and the Games' organisers have expressed that they hope to broadcast to more than 160 countries.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2020-baseball5-european-championship] The **2020 Baseball5 European Championship** was an international baseball5 tournament organized by the WBSC Europe.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2020-baseball5-european-championship] The championship was held from 28 February to 1 March 2020, in Vilnius, Lithuania and was contested between 14 national teams.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2020-baseball5-european-championship] France won the tournament, beating Lithuania in the final 2 matches to 0.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2020-baseball5-european-championship] Russia finished third defeating Italy 2 matches to 0 in the Bronze medal game.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] The **2022 Baseball5 World Cup** was the first edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Mexico City from 7 to 12 November 2022.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Cuba won the tournament, beating Japan in the final 2 matches to 0.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Chinese Taipei finished third defeating Venezuela 2 matches to 0 in the bronze medal game.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 1There was no qualification event for WBSC Americas and WBSC Oceania.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Teams were selected by World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 2In October 2022, WBSC chose Hong Kong to replace Australia.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] The **2022 European Championships** were the second edition of the European Championships.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] It was a multi-sport event which took place in Munich, Germany from 11 to 21 August 2022.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] The event started three days after the closing ceremonies of the Commonwealth Games held in Birmingham, Great Britain.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] Athletics, cycling, triathlon, women's artistic gymnastics, men's artistic gymnastics and rowing returned after appearing in the inaugural Championships in 2018.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] New to this edition of the Championships were beach volleyball, canoe sprint, and, for the first time, a full slate of para-sport events, sport climbing and table tennis.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] Unlike the 2018 European Championships, swimming, diving, artistic swimming and open water swimming were not part of the program of the event, as the European Aquatics Championships were held at the same time but in Rome, Italy.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] Golf, in the form of the European Golf Team Championships, did not return for this edition.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] As a result of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, athletes from Russia and Belarus were banned from competing at the 2022 European Championships.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] Two athletes participated as the Athlete Refugee Team.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] The five British competitors in table tennis were listed as representing England.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2022-european-championships] One athlete was listed as representing World Triathlon.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2023-baseball5-european-championship] The **2023 Baseball5 European Championship** was an international baseball5 tournament organized by the WBSC Europe.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2023-baseball5-european-championship] The championship was held from 7 to 11 November 2023, in the Lithuanian Sports Complex in Druskininkai, Lithuania and was contested between 13 national teams.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2023-baseball5-european-championship] Hosts Lithuania won the tournament, beating France in the final 2 sets to 0, in a replay of the 2020 final (won by France).
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2023-baseball5-european-championship] Spain finished third defeating the Netherlands 2 sets to 1 in the bronze medal game.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/2023-baseball5-european-championship] Lithuania and France qualified for second time in a row to the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup to be held in the Central Harbourfront Event Space in Hong Kong.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] The **Baseball5 European Championship** (European Baseball5 Championship) is the main championship tournament between national Baseball5 teams in Europe, governed by the WBSC Europe.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] The tournament serves as qualifier for the Baseball5 World Cup, with the top two teams qualifying for the world championship.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] France is the most successful team, having won the championship twice.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] The first championship was held in Vilnius, Lithuania in 2020 and was contested between 14 national teams.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] The tournament was won by France, after defeating Lithuania in the final 2 matches to 0.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] Both teams qualified for the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup held in Mexico City.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] The second edition of the tournament was again held in Lithuania, this time in Druskininkai, and featured 13 teams.
[src:baseball5-european-championship/baseball5-european-championship] The championship game was a replay of the 2020 final between France and Lithuania, this time won by the locals, defeating France.
